  "prompt": "Has Voyager-1 confirmed that there are no Planet X and Nemesis star?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, Voyager 1 has not explicitly confirmed the absence of hypothetical celestial bodies such as \"Planet X\" or the star \"Nemesis.\" \n\nThe term \"Planet X\" commonly refers to a theoretical planet beyond Neptune that could explain certain gravitational effects observed in the outer Solar System. However, there is no definitive evidence for such a planet, and various surveys and updates in planetary science have not identified it.\n\n\"Nebula\" or \"Nemesis,\" on the other hand, is a proposed companion star to our Sun, suggested to have caused periodic mass extinctions on Earth due to its hypothetical gravitational influence on comets in the Oort Cloud. However, no evidence has been found to support the existence of Nemesis.\n\nVoyager 1, now in interstellar space, gathers data on cosmic radiation, magnetic fields, and solar wind, but it does not have the capability to directly detect distant super-Earths or stars beyond our solar system as something like a dedicated astronomical survey instrument could.\n\nIn summary, while Voyager 1 has provided valuable data about interstellar environments, it has not directly confirmed or denied the existence of Planet X or Nemesis. Ongoing research and observations in astronomy continue to explore these theories.",
